item.label: Cerebral gyri
item.name: Cerebral gyri
item.description: The surface of the cerebral hemispheres is folded or convoluted into cerebral gyri (the elevations) and cerebral sulci (the valleys).

item.label: Gyrus rectus
item.name: Gyrus rectus
item.description: The gyrus rectus is a slender, straight gyrus on the orbital surface of the frontal lobe.  It is located just medial to the position of the olfactory bulb and olfactory tract. It is involved in limbic system circuits.

item.label: Parahippocampal gyri
item.name: Parahippocampal gyri
item.description: The parahippocampal gyrus is the most medial gyrus on the ventral aspect of the temporal lobe. The hippocampus is cortex that is rolled up inside the parahippocampal gyrus. The rostral portion of this gyrus is the entorhinal cortex.

item.label: Uncus
item.name: Uncus
item.description: The uncus is a bulge on the anterior aspect of the parahippocampal gyrus caused by the underlying amygdala. it can herniate through the tentorial notch in the event of increased intracranial pressure due to a supratentorial space-occupying lesion.

item.label: Cerebral sulci & fissures, Lateral sulci
item.name: Cerebral sulci_fissures L
item.description: A cerebral fissure is AKA a cerebral sulcus (sing.); sulci (pl.).  Fissures are the depressions or grooves between the gyri or convolutions of the cerebral cortex.  Fissure generally refers to a sulcus that is particularly deep.  The terms are used interchangeably in some cases.

item.label: Lamina terminalis
item.name: Lamina terminalis
item.description: The lamina terminalis is a thin membrane at the rostral end of the third ventricle that represents the original rostral extent of the developing telencephalon. It extends from near the rostrum of the corpus callosum down to the optic chiasm and passes immediately anterior to the anterior commissure.

item.label: Hippocampal formation
item.name: Hippocampal formation
item.description: The hippocampus is AKA the hippocampal formation. It is an area of cerebral cortex rolled up inside the medial aspect of the temporal lobe. It is part of the limbic system and functions in the consolidation of new memories of facts and events. It has three subdivisions: the hippocampus proper (Ammon's horn), the dentate gyrus, and the subiculum. The fornix carries the primary output from the hippocampus to the ipsilateral septal area and hypothalamus.

item.label: Dentate gyri
item.name: Dentate gyri
item.description: The dentate gyrus of the hippocampus is one of two interlocking C-shaped gyri constituting the hippocampus. Ammon's horn or the hippocampus proper is the other. The dentate gyrus receives input from the entorhinal cortex and projects to the hippocampus proper.

item.label: Subiculum
item.name: Subiculum
item.description: The subiculum of the hippocampus is a transitional zone of cortex between the hippocampus proper and the entorhinal cortex (rostral part of parahippocampal gyrus). It receives input from the hippocampus proper and is the principal source of the efferents from the hippocampus; these efferents form the alveus and reach the fornix via the fimbria.

item.label: Hippocampus
item.name: Hippocampus
item.description: The hippocampus is AKA the hippocampal formation. It is an area of cerebral cortex rolled up inside the medial aspect of the temporal lobe. It is part of the limbic system and functions in the consolidation of new memories of facts and events. It has three subdivisions: the hippocampus proper (Ammon's horn), the dentate gyrus, and the subiculum. The fornix carries the primary output from the hippocampus to the ipsilateral septal area and hypothalamus.

item.label: Alveus
item.name: Alveus
item.description: The alveus of the hippocampus is a thin sheet of nerve fibers located on the ventricular surface of the hippocampus. Cell bodies of origin are pyramidal neurons in the hippocampus; these nerve fibers aggregate to form the fimbria prior to entering the fornix.

item.label: Fornix, fimbria
item.name: Fornix, fimbria
item.description: The fimbria of the fornix consist of hippocampal efferents that leave the alveus of the hippocampus and continue into the crus of the fornix.

item.label: Claustrum
item.name: Claustrum
item.description: The claustrum is a thin, layered nucleus located between the external and extreme capsules (and thus between the lentiform nucleus and the insula). Function is unknown.

item.label: Amygdala
item.name: Amygdala
item.description: The amygdala consists of a group of nuclei located near the anterior and medial aspect of the temporal lobe, immediately beneath the uncus. Location is immediately anterior to the anterior tip of the inferior horn of the lateral ventricle. Output from the amygdala via the stria terminalis contributes to the major limbic system circuits. Essential role in emotions and their behavioral expression.

item.label: Corpus striatum, Caudate nuclei, Tail
item.name: Corpus striatuCaudate nuc
item.description: The caudate nucleus is the medial portion of the striatum. It consists of a large head that bulges into the anterior horn of the lateral ventricle, a body that narrows and curves along the body of the lateral ventricle and a tail that continues through the atrium or trigone of the lateral ventricle and into the inferior horn of the lateral ventricle. Principal connections are with the prefrontal and other association areas of cerebral cortex.

item.label: Diencephalon
item.name: Diencephalon
item.description: Developmentally, the diencephalon and telencephalon are derived from the most anterior aspect of the developing neural tube, i.e. the prosencephalon. It includes the thalamus, hypothalamus, epithalamus and subthalamus. The retina, optic nerve and tract and neurohypophysis are also considered to be part of the diencephalon since they are formed as outgrowths from the diencephalon.

item.label: Thalamus, Lateral geniculate nucleus
item.name: Thalamus Lateral genicula
item.description: The lateral geniculate thalamic nucleus (LGN) deals with vision.  It receives input from the retina via the optic nerve and tract. It projects to the primary visual cortex in the occipital lobe (cuneus and lingual gyri) via the geniculocalcarine tract.  The geniculocalcarine tract is AKA the optic radiation and travels in both the sublenticular and retrolentricular portions of the internal capsule.

item.label: Hypothalamus
item.name: Hypothalamus
item.description: The hypothalamus is the most inferior of the four divisions of the diencephalon. While quite small, it has multiple important functions. It is the central control center for the autonomic nervous system, part of the limbic system, exerts a powerful influence on pituitary function and generally is responsible for maintaining homeostasis. It consists of multiple nuclei organized into three regions: anterior (suprachiasmatic, supraoptic and paraventricular), tuberal (dorsomedial, ventromedial and arcuate) and posterior (mammillary and posterior).

item.label: Tuberal region
item.name: Tuberal region
item.description: The hypothalamus is the most inferior of the four divisions of the diencephalon. While quite small, it has multiple important functions. It is the central control center for the autonomic nervous system, part of the limbic system, exerts a powerful influence on pituitary function and generally is responsible for maintaining homeostasis. It consists of multiple nuclei organized into three regions: anterior (suprachiasmatic, supraoptic and paraventricular), tuberal (dorsomedial, ventromedial and arcuate) and posterior (mammillary and posterior).

item.label: Mammillary bodies
item.name: Mammillary bodies
item.description: The mammillary bodies are part of the posterior hypothalamus.  They appear from the ventral view of the brain as a pair of rounded elevations. Primary circuitry involves input from the hippocampus via the fornix and output to the anterior nucleus of thalamus via the mammillothalamic tract. They are part of the Papez circuitry of the limbic system.

item.label: Visual pathway
item.name: Visual pathway
item.description: The entire visual pathway begins in the retina and terminates in the calcarine cortex of the occipital lobe.  The components of the pathway are the optic nerve, optic chiasm, optic tract, lateral geniculate nucleus and optic radiations.

item.label: Optic tracts
item.name: Optic tracts
item.description: The Optic tract consists of optic nerve axons that serve the contralateral visual field.  These axons originate in the ipsilateral temporal retina and contralateral nasal retina and terminate in the lateral geniculate nucleus as well as the pretectal area.

item.label: Optic radiation
item.name: Optic radiation
item.description: The Optic Radiation is AKA geniculocalcarine tract. It is a massive bundle of myelinated nerve fibers that originate in the lateral geniculate nucleus of the thalamus and terminate in the upper and lower banks of the calcarine sulcus in the occipital lobe. It travels through the sublenticular and retrolenticular portions of the posterior limb of the internal capsule.

item.label: Line of Gennari
item.name: Line of Gennari
item.description: The Line of Gennari is AKA the Stripe of Gennari.  It is a thin, white stripe in the primary visual cortex of the calcarine cortex. Visual cortex is often called striate cortex because of this line that is visible to the naked eye.

item.label: Midbrain
item.name: Midbrain
item.description: The midbrain is AKA the mesencephalon. Within its parts (tectum, tegmentum, substantia nigra and cerebral crus or basis pedunculi), it contains cranial nerve nuclei, all of the clinically important ascending and descending tracts, etc. It is traversed by the cerebral aqueduct or aqueduct of Sylvius. It originates developmentally from the mesencephalon.

item.label: Tectum
item.name: Tectum
item.description: The tectum is that portion of the midbrain located above the cerebral aqueduct.  It includes the superior and inferior colliculi which are AKA the quadrigeminal bodies.

item.label: Inferior colliculi
item.name: Inferior colliculi
item.description: The brachium of the inferior colliculus is AKA the inferior brachium. It is a band of nerve fibers carrying auditory input from the inferior colliculus of the midbrain to the medial geniculate nucleus of the thalamus. It is clearly visible grossly on the lateral aspect of the midbrain.

item.label: Periaqueductal gray
item.name: Periaqueductal gray
item.description: Periaqueductal gray matter is the area of gray matter surrounding the cerebral aqueduct of the midbrain. Some of the neurons in this area are part of a descending analgesic pathway that relays in the nucleus raphe magnus of the medulla and subsequently blocks pain at the level of the dorsal horn.

item.label: Tegmentum
item.name: Tegmentum
item.description: The tegmentum is that portion of the midbrain that lies between the cerebral aqueduct and the crus cerebri.  It includes the major ascending sensory tracts (medial lemniscus, spinothalamic), the red nucleus and the substantia nigra.

item.label: Red nuclei & capsule
item.name: Red nuclei_capsule
item.description: The red nucleus is a large, round nucleus in the tegmentum of the midbrain that appears pink or red on freshly-sectioned tissue. It is involved with motor control via its connections with the cerebellum. It receives contralateral input from both the dentate and interposed deep cerebellar nuclei; its primary output in the human is to the ipsilateral inferior olivary nucleus via the central tegmental tract. Since the inferior olivary nucleus projects to contralateral cerebellum, the red nucleus is part of a feedback loop to the cerebellum. While the red nucleus gives origin to a significant rubrospinal tract in non-human species, this tract appears to be of limited extent and importance in humans.

item.label: Substantia nigra
item.name: Substantia nigra
item.description: The substantia nigra is a large band-like nucleus in the midbrain located between the crus cerebri and the red nuclei of the tegmentum. It has two parts: 1) a compact portion consisting of closely packed dopaminergic neurons filled with neuromelanin pigment. These neurons project to the striatum & are the ones damaged in Parkinson disease; 2) a reticular portion consisting of loosely packed neurons that receive input from the striatum and project to the thalamus.

item.label: Cerebral crus
item.name: Cerebral crus
item.description: The cerebral crus is AKA the crus cerebri or the basis pedunculi. This most ventral or inferior aspect of the paired cerebral peduncles contains motor axons originating primarily in the cerebral cortex. The bulk of the cerebral crus is made up of the corticospinal, corticobulbar and corticopontine tract fibers that have left the cerebral cortex, traveled through the internal capsule and will terminate in the spinal cord and brain stem.

item.label: Interpeduncular fossa
item.name: Interpeduncular fossa
item.description: The interpeduncular fossa is the space between the cerebral peduncles on the ventral surface of the midbrain.

item.label: Oculomotor nerves
item.name: Oculomotor nerves
item.description: The third or oculomotor cranial nerve provides motor innervation to the ipsilateral medial rectus, superior rectus, inferior rectus, inferior oblique and levator palapebrae muscles that move the eye. It also includes parasympathetic fibers that terminate in the ipsilateral ciliary ganglion; post-ganglionic fibers from the ciliary ganglion innervate the constrictors of the pupil and the ciliary muscles.

item.label: Trochlear nerve
item.name: Trochlear nerve
item.description: The fourth or trochlear cranial nerve innervates the superior oblique muscle of the contralateral eye. It is the only cranial nerve to exit the dorsal aspect of the brainstem. This location is just caudal to the inferior colliculi of the midbrain.

item.label: Cerebellum
item.name: Cerebellum
item.description: The cerebellum is sometimes referred to as the 'small' brain.  It is located within the posterior fossa, superior to the brain stem. It consists of a finely convoluted cortical surface of folia, a central core of white matter (AKA medullary center) and four paired deep nuclei (dentate, emboliform, fastigial and globose) embedded within the white matter core. The cerebellum functions in the planning and coordination of movement.

item.label: Arteries, branches of
item.name: Arteries_branches of
item.description: The arterial supply to the brain is via the paired internal carotid and vertebral arteries. The terminal branches of the internal carotid arteries are the paired anterior and middle cerebral arteries which supply supratentorial structures.  The two vertebral arteries enter the cranial cavity via the foramen magnum; they join one another at the junction of the medulla with the pons to form the basilar artery.  Together the vertebral-basilar system of arteries supplies the structures of the posterior fossa as well as those supratentorial structures supplied by its terminal branches -- the posterior cerebral arteries.

item.label: Anterior cerebral
item.name: Anterior cerebral
item.description: The anterior cerebral artery is the most anterior of the terminal branches of the internal carotid artery. Along with its branches, it curves around the genu and then superior to the corpus callosum to supply the orbital gyri, medial aspect of the frontal lobe, a portion of the parietal lobe and a narrow band along the most superior region of the lateral aspect of the hemisphere. Since the anterior cerebral artery supplies the paracentral lobule which is responsible for sensation and motor control of the contralateral lower extremity, loss of this blood supply results in paralysis and loss of sensation in the contralateral lower extremity.

item.label: Middle cerebral
item.name: Middle cerebral
item.description: The middle cerebral artery is the most posterior of the terminal branches of the internal carotid artery. Along with its branches, it travels through the lateral sulcus to supply the insula, the lateral aspect of the frontal and parietal lobes and the anterior tip of the temporal lobe. Since the middle cerebral artery supplies the pre- and post-central gyri which are responsible for sensation and motor control of the contralateral head, upper extremity and torso, loss of this blood supply results in paralysis and loss of sensation in the contralateral head, upper extremity and torso.

item.label: Posterior cerebral
item.name: Posterior cerebral
item.description: The posterior cerebral arteries are paired vessels formed as the terminal branches of the basilar artery at the level of the midbrain. They are part of the posterior aspect of the circle of Willis and supply the rostral midbrain, posterior thalamus, medial occipital lobe as well as the inferior and medial surfaces of the temporal lobe. Disruption of the posterior cerebral artery may result in blindness in the contralateral visual field since it supplies the visual cortex of the occipital lobe; it may also present as a contralateral upper motor neuron lesion with spastic paralysis of the contralateral body and face as well as an ipsilateral lower motor neuron lesion of the oculomotor nerve/nucleus since it supplies the crus cerebri and oculumotor nerve/nucleus in the midbrain.

item.label: Ventricular system
item.name: Ventricular system
item.description: The ventricular system is a series of interconnected cerebrospinal-filled chambers within the cerebral hemispheres. Cerebrospinal fluid is formed in the choroid plexus located in the lateral, third and fourth ventricles.

item.label: Lateral ventricles, Inferior horn
item.name: Lateral ventricles Inferi
item.description: The inferior horn of the lateral ventricle is AKA the temporal horn. This region of the lateral ventricle extends into the temporal lobe.

item.label: Choroid plexus
item.name: Choroid plexus
item.description: The choroid plexus is the convoluted and highly vascularized structure in the ventricles that is responsible for the production of cerebrospinal fluid.  It is located in the floor of the lateral ventricle as it curves from the body of the ventricle into the inferior horn; it is not present in the anterior or posterior horns of the lateral ventricle.  From the lateral ventricle, the choroid plexus extends through the interventricular foramina of Monro onto the roof of the third ventricle.  In the fourth ventricle the choroid plexus extends downward from the inferior medullary velum that forms part of the roof the ventricle.  The choroid plexus also extends from the fourth ventricle through the foramina of Luschka into the subarachnoid space.

item.label: Cerebral aqueduct
item.name: Cerebral aqueduct
item.description: The cerebral aqueduct is AKA the cerebral aqueduct of Sylvius.  It is a narrow channel within the midbrain through which cerebrospinal fluid flows from the third ventricle into the fourth ventricle.

item.label: Third ventricle
item.name: Third ventricle
item.description: The third ventricle is a single, narrow, vertically-oriented portion of the ventricular system.  It is located between the two halves of the thalamus and hypothalamus.
